{"CHAUD-MEDLEY":[{"def":"The killing of a person in an affray, in the heat of blood, and while under the influence of passion, thus distinguished from chance- medley or killing in self-defense, or in a casual affray.","pos":""}],"CHAUFFER":[{"def":"A table stove or small furnace, usually a cylindrical box of sheet iron, with a grate at the bottem, and an open top.","pos":""}],"CHAUFFEUR":[{"def":"Brigands in bands, who, about 1793, pillaged, burned, and killed in parts of France; -- so called because they used to burn the feet of their victims to extort money.","pos":""}],"CHAUFFEUSE":[{"def":"A woman chauffeur.","pos":""}],"CHAUN":[{"def":"To open; to yawn.","pos":""}],"CHAUNTER":[{"def":"A street seller of ballads and other broadsides.","pos":""},{"def":"A deceitful, tricky dealer or horse jockey.","pos":""}],"CHAUS":[{"def":"a lynxlike animal of Asia and Africa (Lynx Lybicus).","pos":""}],"CHAUSSES":[{"def":"The garment for the legs and feet and for the body below the waist, worn in Europe throughout the Middle Ages; applied also to the armor for the same parts, when fixible, as of chain mail.","pos":""}],"CHAUSSURE":[{"def":"A foot covering of any kind.","pos":""},{"def":"The system of home study established in connection with the summer schools assembled at Chautauqua, N.","pos":""}],"CHAUVINISM":[{"def":"Blind and absurd devotion to a fallen leader or an obsolete cause; hence, absurdly vainglorious or exaggerated patriotism.","pos":""}]}